SIMPLE: waif
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Waif
<hw>Waif</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>waif</ets>,
<ets>gaif</ets>, as adj., lost, unclaimed, <ets>chose gaive</ets> a
waif, LL. <ets>wayfium</ets>, <ets>res vaivae</ets>; of Scand. origin.
See <er>Waive</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Law.)</fld> <def>Goods found of which the
owner is not known; originally, such goods as a pursued thief threw away
to prevent being apprehended, which belonged to the king unless the
owner made pursuit of the felon, took him, and brought him to
justice.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, anything found, or without an owner; that
which comes along, as it were, by chance.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Rolling in his
mind old <xex>waifs</xex> of rhyme.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A wanderer; a castaway; a stray; a homeless
child.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>waif</qex>⟦br⟧
Desirous to return, and not received.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Waift</ent>⟦br⟧
